title: South Cork (UK Parliament constituency)
text:
South Cork, formally known as the Southern division of <a href="County%20Cork">County Cork</a>, was a <a href="United%20Kingdom%20constituencies">parliamentary constituency</a> in <a href="Ireland">Ireland</a>, represented in the <a href="Parliament%20of%20the%20United%20Kingdom">Parliament of the United Kingdom</a>. From 1885 to 1922 it returned one <a href="Member%20of%20Parliament%20%28United%20Kingdom%29">Member of Parliament</a> (MP) to the <a href="House%20of%20Commons%20of%20the%20United%20Kingdom">House of Commons</a> of the <a href="United%20Kingdom%20of%20Great%20Britain%20and%20Ireland">United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland</a>.
Until the <a href="1885%20United%20Kingdom%20general%20election%20in%20Ireland">1885 general election</a> the area was part of the <a href="Cork%20County%20%28UK%20Parliament%20constituency%29">Cork County</a> constituency. From 1922 it was not represented in the <a href="Parliament%20of%20the%20United%20Kingdom">UK Parliament</a>, as it was no longer in the UK.
Boundaries.
This constituency comprised the southern part of <a href="County%20Cork">County Cork</a>, consisting of the barony of East Carbery, West Division, that part of the barony of <a href="Ibane%20and%20Barryroe">Ibane and Barryroe</a> not contained within the constituency of <a href="South%20East%20Cork%20%28UK%20Parliament%20constituency%29">South East Cork</a>, that part of the barony of West Carbery, East Division not contained within the constituency of <a href="West%20Cork%20%28UK%20Parliament%20constituency%29">West Cork</a>, and that part of the barony of East Carbery, East Division contained within the parishes of Ballymoney, Desert, Desertserges, Island, Kilgarriff, Kilnagross and Templebryan.
